Class CommandShell

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.uidaho.junicon.interpreter.interpreter.PropertiesExtender
      • edu.uidaho.junicon.interpreter.interpreter.Environment

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IDispatcher, IEnvironment, IInterpreter, IInterpreterContext, IInterpreterSetters, IPropertiesExtender, IThreadResolver

    public class CommandShell
extends AbstractShell
    CommandShell is an outer interpretive shell implemented using a transformational meta-interpreter. The command shell detects complete statements and their target language, and then dispatches them to the appropriate sub-interpreter to parse, transform, and execute on a script engine substrate. The command shell will either interpret, translate, compile, or extract. These options are mutually exclusive. The compile and extract options are ignored if useCmdFile() is off. Otherwise, to compile or extract, the command shell will invoke a futher cmd file to perform the work. If compiling and the file does not end in Java, it will first be translated. If explicitly asked to translate, any compile or extract options are ignored.

      • setCommandPrefix

        public void setCommandPrefix(String commandPrefix)
        Sets the command prefix, which is prepended to "/command" to yield "prefix.command()". Commands are of the form: 
                /id.id...               => prefix.id...()
        /id.id... expr ...      => prefix.id...(expr,...)
        which are translated into method calls, typically prefixed with a shell class that is statically imported. Commands are also of the form: 
                id.id... expr ...       => id...(expr,...)
        that allows a style of method invocation that omits parenthesis.

      • getCommandPrefix

        public String getCommandPrefix()
        Gets the command prefix, which is prepended to "/command" to yield "prefix.command()".

      • setIsJavaSyntax

        public void setIsJavaSyntax()
        Use Java syntax. Use = for assign, == for compare, var for variable declarations, and def for method definitions.

      • main

        public static void main(String[] args)
        Main method to run the interpreter. Spring first creates the shell and its dependencies, then processes command line arguments to override Spring configuration file settings. The Spring configuration filename is taken from the "junicon.spring.config" system property if it is set, in which case a file system application context is created. Otherwise Spring configuration is from the classpath using "config/startup/spring_config.xml".
        Parameters:
        args - command line arguments, will override Spring settings.

      • handleDirective

        public String handleDirective(String line)
                       throws InterpreterException
        Handle a transform directive given by a scoped annotation. If a line, outside of any statement, starts with @<script lang="..."> any contents up to an ending @</script> tag are directly passed to the substrate interpreter without preprocessing or transformation. If inside another statement, such a script annotation will be turned into an annotated block quote @<script>{< code >} and then later transformed from to IconInvokeIterator(()->{code}).

        Otherwise, if a line in a file starts with @<tag attr="..."> (or without the quotes), the given interpreter property name.attr is set from that value, and an ending @</name.attr> tag resets the property to its previous value.

        Commented scoped annotations of the form #@<tag attr="..."> or #@</tag> are treated in the same way as scoped annotations.

        We currently do not allow nested transform directives.

        Specified by:
        handleDirective in interface IInterpreter
        Overrides:
        handleDirective in class AbstractShell
        Returns:
        non-null text to continue processing, or null if directive was consumed.
        Throws:
        InterpreterException
